{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17595473","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17595473"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T11:04:35+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T11:04:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15359"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15359","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15359"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.4,0.16,0.16,0.2]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8050"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68540"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8050","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8050"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15359"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53996"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4944"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7882"},{"type":"tags","id":"8755"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19547"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19549"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68540","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/68540"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA medical student is reviewing the natural history of chronic hepatitis B virus infection. The infection typically progresses through several distinct phases.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the inactive carrier phase of chronic hepatitis B infection?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["High viral DNA levels with elevated liver enzymes","Low viral DNA levels with normal liver enzymes","High viral DNA levels with normal liver enzymes","Low viral DNA levels with elevated liver enzymes","Undetectable viral DNA with normal liver enzymes"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe natural history of chronic hepatitis B infection typically progresses through several phases:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHigh viral DNA levels with elevated liver enzymes\u003C/strong\u003E characterises the immune active phase\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELow viral DNA levels with normal liver enzymes\u003C/strong\u003E defines the inactive carrier phase, where patients maintain positive hepatitis B surface antigen but have low viral replication\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHigh viral DNA levels with normal liver enzymes\u003C/strong\u003E occurs during the immune tolerant phase\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELow viral DNA levels with elevated liver enzymes\u003C/strong\u003E is not typical of any specific phase\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUndetectable viral DNA with normal liver enzymes\u003C/strong\u003E represents viral clearance or resolution, not the inactive carrier phase\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDuring the inactive carrier phase, patients have positive hepatitis B surface antigen, low viral DNA levels (typically \u003C2000 IU/mL), and normal alanine aminotransferase levels. This phase can last for years or decades and carries a relatively good prognosis with low risk of progression to cirrhosis or hepatocellular carcinoma.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Chronic hepatitis B infection progresses through distinct phases: immune tolerant, immune active, inactive carrier, and reactivation phases.","The inactive carrier phase is characterised by positive hepatitis B surface antigen, low viral DNA levels (\u003C2000 IU/mL), and normal alanine aminotransferase.","Understanding the natural history of chronic hepatitis B infection is crucial for monitoring and management decisions."],"references":["Mehta P, Grant LM, Reddivari AKR. Viral Hepatitis. 2024 Mar 10. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 32119436","Lok AS, Pawlotsky JM. Viral hepatitis at a crossroad. Gastroenterology. 2012 May;142(6):1261-3. doi: 10.1053/j.gastro.2012.03.007. PMID: 22537431","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Scienc","Song JE, Kim DY. Diagnosis of hepatitis B. Ann Transl Med. 2016 Sep;4(18):338. doi: 10.21037/atm.2016.09.11. PMID: 27761442; PMCID: PMC5066055"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53996"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15359"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53996","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/53996"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-09T20:21:49+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-09T20:22:38+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8050"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68540"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"